<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-10-08T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-10-08T20:00:00-05:00" n="152" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d152">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5 Submarines/24: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-08T20:00:00-05:00">October 8,
                                    1936—8 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>367. Your 462, October 6, 2 p.m. You are authorized to sign the
                            procès-verbal designed to obtain further accessions to the rules of
                            international law concerning submarine warfare. Full Power has been
                            signed by the President and is being mailed by pouch today.</p>
                        <p>Should it be desired to sign the procès-verbal before the receipt of the
                            Full Power, it is hoped that the present telegram will be considered
                            sufficient evidence of your authority to sign that instrument.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>